al riches of Frank Leslie's newspaper and the only study to situate these images fully within the social context of Gilded Age America. Beyond the Lines illuminates the role of illustration in nineteenth-century America and gives us a new look at how the social milieu shaped the practice of illustrated journalism and was in turn shaped by it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aIllustrated periodicalszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aIllustrated periodicals. 7aART / American / General.2bisacsh  aantebellum america.  acivil war.  aengravers.  afrank leslie.  agilded age.  aharpers weekly.  ahistory.  aillustrated newspaper.  aillustrations.  ajournalism.  alabor conditions.  alabor.  amedia studies.  anew york daily graphic.  anewspapers.  anonfiction.  apictorial reporting.  apolitical movements.  apolitics.  apoverty.  aprogressive era.  areconstruction.  areporters.  asocial change.  asocial issues.  asocial movements.  astrikes.  aunions.  avisual culture.  avisual journalism.  avisual media.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024814440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520939745?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520939745423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520939745/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY